{{Commons category|High Sheriffs of Wiltshire}}\n*[http://www.tudorplace.com.ar/Documents/sheriffs_of_wiltshire.htm The Occupants of the Ancient office of High Sheriff of Wiltshire from 1067 to 1612] page at tudorplace.com.ar\n\n{{High Shrievalties}}\n\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Wiltshire| ]]\n[[Category:High Shrievalties in England|Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:History of Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:People from Wiltshire| ]]\n[[Category:Wiltshire-related lists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ceremonial officer in Wiltshire}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\nThis is a list of Sheriffs and (after 1 April 1974) '''[[High Sheriff]]s of [[Wiltshire]]'''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1972/70/section/219Local |title=Government Act 1972: Section 219 }}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nUntil the 14th century the shrievalty was held ''[[ex officio]]'' by the [[castellan]]s of [[Old Sarum]].\n\nOn 1 April 1974, under the provisions of the [[Local Government Act 1972]], the title of Sheriff of Wiltshire was retitled High Sheriff of Wiltshire.<ref>\"Sheriffs appointed for a county or Greater London shall be known as high sheriffs, and any reference in any enactment or instrument to a sheriff shall be construed accordingly in relation to sheriffs for a county or Greater London.\" ({{cite web |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1972/70/section/219Local |title=Government Act 1972: Section 219 }}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }})</ref>\n\n{{Expand list|date=August 2008}}\n[[File:Sir_Richard_Colt_Hoare_monument,_Salisbury_Cathedral.jpg|thumb|200px|Monument to [[Sir Richard Hoare, 2nd Baronet|Sir Richard Colt Hoare]], Sheriff of Wiltshire in 1805, in [[Salisbury Cathedral]] ]]\n\n==Sheriff==\n\n===To 1400===\n{{colbegin}}\n*1066: Edric\n*1067\u20131070: Philippe de Buckland\n*1085: Aiulphus the Sheriff\n*1070\u20131105: [[Edward of Salisbury]]\n*1110: William of Pont de L'Arche<ref>[https://archive.org/details/regestaregumangl02davi/page/n8 Davis, \"Regesta Regnum Anglo-Normannum\", p93, Entry 948, Oxford, 1956] at archive.org</ref>\n*1119: Edward d'\u00c9vreux\n*1120: Humphrey \"The Great\" De BOHUN (2\u00ba B. Bohun of Taterford) \u2013 Bearer of the Royal Standard in 1120 in the battle of Benneville in Normandy\n*????: Walter FitzEdward of Salisbury<ref>[http://homepages.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~pmcbride/rfc/sheriffs.htm Rootsweb]</ref>\n*1130: Warin de Lisures or Lisoriis\n*????: \"William the Late Sheriff\", so called in 1155\n*1152\u20131159: [[Patrick of Salisbury, 1st Earl of Salisbury]]<ref>He was already Sheriff in October 1152, when he was addressed as \"Earl Patrick, sheriff\" in a writ of Stephen: [[George Cokayne]], ''Complete Peerage'', vol. XI, p. 37, note (e)</ref>\n*1160\u20131162: Richard ''Clericus'' (Richard de Wilton)\n*1163: Milo de Dauntesey\n*1164\u20131181: Richard de Wilton or de Wilteshire\n*1181: Michael Belet and Robert Malde (Mauduit)\n*1182: ditto 1181 and Roger Fitz Renfr or Renf\n*1183\u20131187: Robert Mauduit\n*1189: [[Hugh Bardolf]]\n*1190: [[William of Salisbury, 2nd Earl of Salisbury]], son of [[Patrick of Salisbury, 1st Earl of Salisbury|Patrick]]\n*1191: Robert de Tregoz\n*1192: William d'\u00c9vreux (as above)\n*1193\u20131197: William d'\u00c9vreux (as above) and Thomas d'\u00c9vreux (otherwise Devereux) his son\n*1197\u20131198: [[Stephen of Thornham]] and Alexander de Ros\n*1199: [[Stephen of Thornham]] and Wandragesil de Courselles\n*1200\u20131203: [[William Longesp\u00e9e, 3rd Earl of Salisbury|William Longespee, 3rd Earl of Salisbury]] and Robert de Berneres\n*1207: Geoffrey de Neville\n*1210: [[Robert de Vieuxpont|Robert de Veteriponte]](i.e. de Vipont) jointly with Nicholas de Vipont\n*1211\u20131212: [[Robert de Vieuxpont|Robert de Veteriponte]](i.e. de Vipont)\n*1215\u20131225: [[William Longesp\u00e9e, 3rd Earl of Salisbury